(41, 3, 'The System of Monarchy: The Government that is Truly of The People and For the People', NULL, '<p style=\"margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:&quot;Arial&quot;,sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\" id=\"isPasted\"><span style=\"font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:&quot;Times New Roman&quot;,serif;\">With the incessant downfall pertaining to the economy of the Philippines, should not it be the case that the country should adapt from a democratic to a monarchical system? While republic countries like the Philippines spend their time dancing and playing ubiquitous songs for the voters\' approval every three years, monarchical countries such as Luxembourg keep themselves busy improvin', 0, '2023-12-08 14:03:17', NULL, '2023-12-08 07:03:17', '<p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\' id=\"isPasted\"><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>With the incessant downfall pertaining to the economy of the Philippines, should not it be the case that the country should adapt from a democratic to a monarchical system? While republic countries like the Philippines spend their time dancing and playing ubiquitous songs for the voters&#39; approval every three years, monarchical countries such as Luxembourg keep themselves busy improving their land and their resources utilized. For years now, the Philippines has had its fair share of struggles with its scarcity of resources available in the country. The economy has been gauged as a problem for centuries (Bello et al., 2005). The year 1946, the Philippines was given its independence after a tedious process of back-and-forth war between countries. Starting as an economic powerhouse, the Philippines, withholding their eagerness to develop, eventually fell out of glory after the revisionism of the rules of trade relations with the Americans. This trade arrangement gave the Philippines considerable strides in economic development (Sicat, 2021). Adapting the system of democracy, although it gave people a voice and platform, had many repercussions on the economic system, one of which was its costly spending during the 2022 elections, amounting to around 4.7 billion pesos, or 8.3 million dollars, an expenditure unknown to a monarchical-ruled country.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>A historical system pioneered during 3000 BC, monarchy is a well-known sovereignty of a monarch over their country&#39;s domain &mdash;until they meet their demise (Wilde, 2021). On the one hand, absolute monarchy exists, where the ruler possesses an insurmountable amount of power among their constituents. Some countries under such rule include the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia. On the other hand, the constitutional monarchy serves as a parliamentary system where the monarch acts as a head of state and performs certain ceremonial duties, and serves as a symbol for the country. Although the monarch has a smaller scale of power in the constitutional monarchy, the system proved to be compelling pertaining to the economy as countries such as Japan and Luxembourg as significant representations of the arrangement.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>Although there are a lot of factors from both systems that affect the decision of completely overriding the existing ruling, the essence of the paper is concentrated on only one aspect- the economy. Numerous metrics can be used to rank the top economies in the world&mdash;the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) per capita is one of these metrics and arguably the most appropriate metric for ranking the top countries economically. GOBankingRates (2020), with data from the World Bank and the Central Intelligence Agency, ranked the top 50 nations by their GDP per capita (as cited in Csiszar, 2020). 21 of the 43 monarchical countries are included on the list&mdash;with half of the top 20 also being under monarchs, such as Luxembourg, Saudi Arabia, Monaco, and Liechtenstein. With actual exemplification of countries represented by the data they provide, should not it be early evidence as to why the Philippines must adopt a monarchical type of ruling? A system that efficiently developed numerous economies rapidly, contrary to the widespread belief that monarchy could not keep up with modernity due to its traditional nature.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;\'><strong><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>Pure Economic Comparison:</span></strong></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>A good representation of a leading country under a monarchical system, Luxembourg is a well-known, economically successful country that the Philippines must adapt due to its uniqueness, accomplished economy, and the quality of life of its constituents. This small country has one of the most successful economies with a stable high income and has historically recorded a solid growth rate while exhibiting low inflation and unemployment rate. Based on the statistics provided by Heritage (2022), the country of Luxembourg has one of the highest GDP (Gross Domestic Product) among all countries in the world, with $118,002 per capita. In addition, unlike our country&rsquo;s providence, Luxembourg&#39;s prosperous economy is still improving, having a 2.1% annual growth in a 5-year compound despite facing difficulties as a country, one example of which is the COVID-19 pandemic, whereas the country&#39;s economy contracted by 1.3% in 2020 (Heritage, 2022). In addition to Luxembourg&#39;s flourishing economy, the country also has a stable monetary system and quality of life based on its economy, freedom, and rights. According to Heritage, Luxembourg has an open and unrestricted rule on foreign ownership, transfers, and taxes (Mahler, 2006). Domiciled assets and investment funds in the country are second only to the United States since the legal system of Luxembourg provides aid and protection for the procurement and disposition of every property right owned by anyone living in their state. In contrast to the Philippines&rsquo; foreign investment act, or R.A. no. 11647, the Philippines has had a problem attracting foreign investors due to their lack of management control and over-regulation due to their protection for local brands (Standen &amp; Medina, 2022). Although recently amended by former president Rodrigo Duterte, it lacks in comparison to Luxembourg&rsquo;s openness in trading and foreign investments, making them ranked 8th in the 2021 edition of the Global Financial Centre&#39;s Index (Lux Innovation, 2021).&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>One reason Luxembourg&rsquo;s system could be adapted by the Philippines is due to the flexible fiscal system, being an essential part of the country&#39;s economy and has been a huge factor in the country&#39;s wealth. According to the Cr&eacute;dit Agricole Group (2022), one-third of the country&#39;s GDP is driven by the financial sector, which includes international private and wealth management and various business banking models. The country has been a stable provider across the whole of Europe, having the highest GDP on the continent. Although the first in GDP per capita, the country itself is very dependent on its partners in the continent. One advantage of Luxembourg is its openness to international business and services. Luxembourg&#39;s international trade represented 390.3% of its GDP in 2020 (World Bank, 2020, as cited in Cr&eacute;dit Agricole Group, 2022). This is where the fiscal system led by the monarchy of Luxembourg becomes beneficial for the economy of the country. According to Neugarten (2021), Luxembourg has one of the largest investment funds and banking operations that must be adapted due to its tax policies and is regarded as a &quot;tax haven&quot; country. Since one-third of the country is driven by this sector of the economy, Luxembourg provides a healthy and satisfactory relationship to investors outside of their country because of their laws and regulation, thus generating more tax revenue, more money, more job opportunities for residents, and provide more profitable business connections. In the Philippines, although the country&rsquo;s fiscal system gradually improved through the years, the Philippines&rsquo; system has been a detriment to the country&rsquo;s development. Diokno (2021) mentioned the ineffectiveness of the system due to its noticeable flaws. Around 75% of Filipinos do not utilize the investments, which restricts them from rendering benefits for the country&rsquo;s constituents. Another reason is the financial system of the Philippines is not flexible due to its country&rsquo;s own restrictions. USA.gov (2019) rated the Philippines as ranked 124th out of 190 countries in the &ldquo;ease of doing business&rdquo; for foreign investors. One reason is due to the country&rsquo;s high corruption index at 117th place at the 2021 year mark (Transparency International, 2021), making them inefficient for generating a profit and being a negative indicator for foreign investors.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>Unlike the Philippines&rsquo; laws and regulations, Luxembourg&#39;s taxation system and laws are one of the main reasons it is a successful country economically and a great country for foreign and local businesses. According to Hayden Economics (2022), a &quot;tax haven&quot; country like Luxembourg provides efficient and secured usage of tax and has an exceptionally low or sometimes no tax rate for clients, whether they are residents or non-residents of the country. Mainly because of the country&#39;s laws and policies that provide essential and adequate service for its constituents. De Mooij et al. (2020) stated that multinational corporations provide investments in the country due to its regulations on international tax rules and its ample and reasonably generous tax exemption regime. Luxembourg&#39;s bilateral tax treaties provide lower withholding tax (WHT) on incoming flows from a foreign country. In addition, the monarchy has gradually changed the international tax system over the years to enhance the movement and mobilization of revenue. According to the Tax Foundation (n.d.), Luxembourg has been active in the alignment between the country and other neighboring countries&#39; tax treaties, a venture to tackle the problems of double taxation in two countries. Countries such as Luxembourg attract foreign investments due to its greater number of partners that will minimize the withholding tax in investments between countries. Although the country only has around 630,000 individuals in its population, Luxembourg attracts investors as much as the United States since the mobilization of money is fluid and flows into the corporation, minimizing the taxes being applied to the corporate entity (Neguarten, 2021). The sovereign and monarchical system of Luxembourg has found an effective way of handling the country&#39;s financial stability. In contrast, the taxation of the Philippines was deemed inefficient and anti-poor. Punongbayan (2017) stated that the taxation system of the Philippines burdens the poor as it provides little to no support for the business and economic aspects, but instead focuses on the limitations of Value Added Tax, which explains the low tax revenue the Filipino people receive. Moreover, according to Teo (2020), the Philippines has the highest corporate tax, a taxation practice that taxes the profits of corporations, a system unfamiliar with the monarchical system such as Luxembourg&rsquo;s. With this, the Philippines might scare off foreign investors and corporations that have the idea to boost the economy of the country, something Luxembourg takes advantage of.&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>Through a productive tax and fiscal system, as well as a stable constitution and laws, Luxembourg has been an economically affluent and developed country in the world, making it cheaper to run the country through its system compared to the democratic system of the Philippines. According to Standard &amp; Poors (n.d., as cited in Cosgrave, 2015), it is indicated that monarchical countries are reliable on credit and have higher value of balance sheets compared to their republic counterparts. Additionally, it is also stated that monarchies have significant issuance of debts and bonds and provide reparation more than any other system at 40%. This small country has one of the most successful economies with a stable high income and has historically recorded a solid growth rate while exhibiting low inflation and unemployment rate, upheld by its historically low poverty rate of 0.30% in 2019 ((Macrotrends, 2022). While having a significantly lower number of citizens with 639,070 during 2021, a much lower number compared to the Philippines&rsquo; 111 million, they managed to have a spurring economic growth rate. One major reason for this is although Luxembourg is an exceptionally wealthy country, the monarchical system of the country creates a cheaper approach to elections and ruling. Although monarchical countries have a relatively higher tax than democratic countries due to their monarchy&rsquo;s royal tax, the sovereign grant funds are fundamentally advantageous for the country. According to Chang (2022), Although people annually pay for the government funding of the royal family at an estimation of $1.48 per person or at $98.84 million for the monarchy funding, it is much cheaper to run a country, especially during elections. In the 2022 elections alone, the national candidate body spent around 4.9 billion pesos, a sizable value considering the wealth of the Philippines, in comparison to the wealth of Luxembourg (De Leon, 2022).&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;\'><strong><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>Stability comparison:</span></strong></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-bottom:12.0pt;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>As a democratic country, the Philippines&#39; authorities have a time restriction for demonstrating their worth and initiatives to their people, resulting in frequent shifts of political viewpoint in the chair of power. According to Olofsgard (2022), shifting political power, particularly when there is a rivalry in place, can contribute to economic instability since certain political personalities and parties demonstrate conflict and greediness, which can lead to self-enrichment rather than country progress. Political rivalry may be beneficial if there are no problems inside one country&#39;s administration. However, given the Philippines&#39; tumultuous history, political shifting may not be a wise idea in order to maintain this system of government. One example is the perilous junction of personal and political antagonism, as well as the tense succession between the Marcoses and the Aquinos (Quimpo, 2007). Because the Philippines has a long history of democracy, this problem has contributed to and spurred competition between the parties. Politics with ever-changing officials is difficult since people and parties have diverse views, thoughts, and goals that might have an impact on the economy in the future (Olofsgard, 2022). This issue may have an impact on business laws, which might be disastrous for the country&#39;s investors and customers. Individuals who are afraid of taking risks tend to hold back, and unstable countries frequently see lower investments in physical capital and education. Higher government turnover rates significantly reduce economic and statistical growth (Olofsgard, 2022). Furthermore, if there is instability, it would be difficult for the country since many persons and parties will not know who is to be accountable for the crisis. It may then be difficult to establish a lasting republic, and democratic change will have to occur under a monarchy&#39;s protection and direction. It is a deeply rooted type of governance that continues to enjoy popular support from its citizens (Bulmer, 2017). In such cases, a monarch willing and competent to serve as a non-executive head of state might provide vital legitimacy and continuity, facilitating the effective construction of democratic constitutional order and strengthening democratic constitution-building.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;\'><strong><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>The response to the anomaly of the two systems:</span></strong></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#0E101A;\'>The difficulty of democracy is that it is a rather inefficient form of administration since everyone has the chance to express themselves, which is a wonderful thing in and of itself. It does, however, have an effect on the time it takes to make a decision. As a result, if there is a crisis or a situation that necessitates an immediate call to action, the response will be delayed since there is a lot of deliberation and voting before a decision is made. Their culture of decisiveness is different when contrasted to democracy. Monarchy is an efficient form of governance since choices are made by the ruling elite. The day after a general election, the King requests the leader of the party with the most seats in the House of Commons to become Prime Minister and form a government (UK Parliament, n.d.). Thus, the power to propose and implement laws is held by an elected Parliament (Royal.UK, n.d.), whereas the Sovereign focuses on certain parts of duties that aim for the nation&#39;s stability and continuation.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#0E101A;\'>The democratic governance situation in the Philippines has stalled negatively, as people-elected politicians have exploited their position to enhance their lifestyles further&mdash;this is also true for different government institutions. Because of the slow process, the corrupt institutions and people may continue to wreak havoc on the people whom they swear to serve. The Priority Development Assistance Fund fraud, popularly known as the pork barrel scam, began in 2003 and ended in 2013. The PDAF&#39;s principal purpose was to provide politicians with a lump sum of the budget to devote to their initiatives. This, however, was exploited and utilized to defraud the people of almost ten billion pesos (Limpot, 2021). The corruption does not stop there since Philippine politicians and officials have been embroiled in a number of scandals, including the BNPP, NBN-ZTE, ill-gotten money, and a variety of other heinous acts. This highlights the inevitability of corruption in the Philippines, even with the &quot;reformed&quot; system it has gone through.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#0E101A;\'>On the contrary, the monarchical viewpoint differs and has the actual authority to balance such scandals and power abuse, which is known as countervailing.&nbsp;</span><em><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>Countervailing</span></em><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>&nbsp;is a power that the monarch can use to balance out the country&#39;s governance (Guillen, 2021). Furthermore, if a particular arm of government under a constitutional monarchy is not operating effectively, countervailing power is the solution. Monarchies, on the other hand, are no strangers to corruption. There are corruptions in monarchical regimes, and scandals in royal families, and one can go on and on, but the power balance between the government and the monarch mitigates this. Thus, the perpetrators of corruption are prevented from causing more harm to the country.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#0E101A;\'>&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:justify;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#0E101A;\'>&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#0E101A;\'>The Republic of the Philippines, like everything else in the world, has its ups and downs. When the republic reaches a high point&mdash;when everyone&#39;s rights are recognized and safeguarded by the state&mdash;it descends to a low point&mdash;when the wrong people are placed in charge and begin abusing their authority and its citizens. No matter how many individuals demonstrate their patriotism or national pride, there will always be others who are dissatisfied with the republic. If the majority felt comfortable about being heard, the minority was probably unhappy about not being heard frequently enough. One of the most astonishing aspects of living in a republic is that everyone has a voice in major problems and policies that influence everyone&#39;s lives. However, that idea broke apart when it became clear that the majority of the participants had no understanding of what they were talking about or doing. The argument is that while a republic system has many advantages, it is not without its drawbacks. The question is whether the benefits have improved people&#39;s lives sufficiently to justify disregarding the disadvantages and continuing the country&#39;s journey under a republic administration. Because the Philippines has made little progress, and some would argue that it has regressed, despite being a democratic nation for so long, a new, more effective system must develop gradually and, little by bit, change the course of our wonderful and cherished nation.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:justify;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#0E101A;\'>&nbsp;</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#0E101A;\'>The evidence suggests that the monarchical system of government offers much more to the country it encompasses. The system is best shown by Luxembourg, a little country compared to its neighbours. Luxembourg has selected which component of their country they wish to focus on through the monarchical structure of the country. Luxembourg has been a major economic success because of the correct framework, equitable and attentive laws and regulations, and a flexible fiscal and taxation structure. Their functioning government structure is a critical component of their success. This exemplification and along with the many benefits that the monarchy system offers demonstrates that the economic foundation of monarchical countries, as well as the poor leadership of presidents in the democratic administration of the Philippines, should enable citizens to see the possibilities of transitioning from democratic governance to monarchical guidance. The Philippines needs to adopt the monarchical system of other prosperous countries rather than retaining its current democratic system if it ever hopes to escape the ever-worsening deprivation that has gripped the country in recent decades.</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:center;\'><strong><span style=\'font-size:20px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>References</span></strong></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;\'><strong><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>&nbsp;</span></strong></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>2021 corruption perceptions index - explore the results. Transparency.org. (n.d.). https://www.transparency.org/en/cpi/2021</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>Bello, W., de Guzman, M., Malig, M. &amp; Docena, H. (2004). The anti-development state: The political economy of permanent crisis in the Philippines. <em>Zed Books.</em></span><a href=\"https://books.google.com.ph/books?hl=en&lr=&id=3S0ukwMn8LoC&oi=fnd&pg=PR7&dq=economy+of+the+philippines&ots=ifiiJ8KoMp&sig=EJoydWQNTbJnWSewVZ2VVmQPkj0&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false\"><em><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:windowtext;text-decoration:none;\'>&nbsp;</span></em></a><a href=\"https://books.google.com.ph/books?hl=en&lr=&id=3S0ukwMn8LoC&oi=fnd&pg=PR7&dq=economy+of+the+philippines&ots=ifiiJ8KoMp&sig=EJoydWQNTbJnWSewVZ2VVmQPkj0&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false\"><em><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;color:#1155CC;\'>https://books.google.com.ph/books?hl=en&amp;lr=&amp;id=3S0ukwMn8LoC&amp;oi=fnd&amp;pg=PR7&amp;dq=economy+of+the+philippines&amp;ots=ifiiJ8KoMp&amp;sig=EJoydWQNTbJnWSewVZ2VVmQPkj0&amp;redir_esc=y#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false</span></em></a></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>&nbsp; &nbsp;Cosgrave, J. (2015, August 7). Is having a monarchy better for your economy? CNBC. https://www.cnbc.com/2015/08/07/is-having-a-monarchy-better-for-your- economy.html</span></p><p style=\'margin:0cm;line-height:200%;font-size:15px;font-family:\"Arial\",sans-serif;margin-top:12.0pt;margin-right:0cm;margin-bottom:12.0pt;margin-left:0cm;text-align:justify;text-indent:36.0pt;\'><span style=\'font-size:16px;line-height:200%;font-family:\"Times New Roman\",serif;\'>Cr&eacute;dit