(42, 1, 'Diaspora\'s Relevance', NULL, '<p id=\"isPasted\">Art is a constantly evolving practice, but in its pursuit of the novel and innovative, it is drifting away from tradition and origin. This certainly causes plenty of problems for artists who want to produce something new whilst retaining the integrity of the original identity of a form of art. Despite its paradoxical implications, artists from different facets and types of art have been trying to solve this problem. This synthesis paper aims to at least give a gist of the struggles, challenges, and attempts to solve the problem of taking the authentic identity of a specific art form and integrating it with global modernization coming from different places.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 0, '2023-12-08 14:05:24', NULL, '2023-12-08 07:05:24', '<p id=\"isPasted\">Art is a constantly evolving practice, but in its pursuit of the novel and innovative, it is drifting away from tradition and origin. This certainly causes plenty of problems for artists who want to produce something new whilst retaining the integrity of the original identity of a form of art. Despite its paradoxical implications, artists from different facets and types of art have been trying to solve this problem. This synthesis paper aims to at least give a gist of the struggles, challenges, and attempts to solve the problem of taking the authentic identity of a specific art form and integrating it with global modernization coming from different places.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>First, the diaspora and the fluidity of its location provide diasporic experiences. Diasporic fictions all essentially communicate one set of things&mdash;about protagonists commonly parting away from their original homes and trying to imitate their current home&#39;s culture. But upon doing so, they experience the same struggles &mdash; their original identities sprouting no matter how much they try to bury and replace it with new ones. An experience that is said to symbolize the conflict between the &ldquo;I&rdquo; and the &ldquo;world&rdquo; (Reyes, 2017). Even to the author, the <em>self</em> in diasporic literature is frequently not immediately visible. This is due to the constant change in the narrative threads, symbolic images, and material components that comprise the self (Reyes, 2017). This constant motion was also observed by Marcel Duchamp based on the article written by Marcus Moore (2011). According to Moore (2011), Marcel Duchamp&rsquo;s two artefacts, a &ldquo;postcard home&rdquo; and &ldquo;Bo&icirc;te-en-Valise&rdquo; shaped his ideals and perception about the constant motion of how he define the meaning of his different artworks. Marcel Duchamp&rsquo;s &ldquo;Bo&icirc;te-en-Valise,&rdquo; a suitcase containing images of his &ldquo;readymade,&rdquo; encapsulated the unpleasant impacts of relocation, a state of transition and a sense of having left one&#39;s native culture (Moore, 2011). Duchamp&rsquo;s &ldquo;readymade&rdquo; only grew popularity 50 years after, what&rsquo;s beautiful about this is that he intentionally twisted and willfully misinterpreted the meaning of his art and his memories. This approach reveal his personality, rather than historical accuracy (Moore, 2011). Old memory became something new after years that memory was created in the physical world for the sake of adopting to the current person&rsquo;s identity and the present and everchanging times. This everchanging phenomena is very similar to what was indicated in the article of Flores (2017a) about the conflict between art history and globalization. In the said article, Flores said that the documentation of art history got tricker because of the decolonialization that happened throughout the world. The mainstream and western way of analyzing and documentation of different types of art is of no use anymore and should be reconceptualize and recalibrated Flores (2017a).&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>In the Philippines, however, the &quot;authentic&quot; identity was skewed by their colonizers. In colonial times, the urban metropole was a &quot;tool of conquest&quot; that enabled the creation of colonies that were both politically submissive and economically profitable for the colonizers. Moreover, Lico &amp; Tomacruz (2015) point out that the provision of new urban technologies and other metropolitan services by the colonizers was not exclusively a gesture of colonial benevolence to ameliorate the backward lives of native Filipinos. Instead, they used it for exploitation and their own personal gains. In addition, Lico &amp; Tomacruz (2015) also note that the ingenious network of technologically advanced colonial infrastructure enabled resource development, extraction, and exploitation that was channeled to the colonial capital to maintain Manila&#39;s status as the seat of colonial power and a significant commercial entrepot of the empire back in the Spanish era. However this doesn&rsquo;t stop Ferdinant Marcos on pursuing the ideological proposition of making the Philippines &ldquo;great again&rdquo; when he won his first presidential election in 1965 (Flores, 2017b). The Marcos regime actively promoted this ideology effectively to its people through discourses on development, identity, and democracy, according to Flores (2017b), who also described how the three discourses exemplifies the logic and feelings of modernity and internationalism by being progressive, true to an imagined authentic origin, and liberated. Marcos&#39; offer of democracy and funding of aesthetic endeavors within the framework of their filial and clientelist relationship made the arts appear more personal and tied to culture, society, and the people.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; To sum it all up, the gaps mentioned above are still being bridged by modern artists. It is an ongoing journey to discover the solutions to these problems. Furthermore, it is a continuous transition that everyone must embrace. But with this, artists must keep in mind that the identity of art is ever changing. In this light, there is one thing this paper presents, the true key for art to have its own identity is to remain to its core.&nbsp;</p>', 'public');
